<br>
Here are my suggestions for melees on how to not break mez unless they are designated to do so. Please feel free to add any tips. <br>
<br>
1. Find out who the MT (main tank) or MA (main assist) is and make an assist key. <br>
<br>
2. Find out who the SA (secondary assist) is and make an assist key. This is in case you have to split tank mobs or MT goes down.<br>
<br>
3. Turn off auto attack, /attack off. I see this breaking mez more than any other single factor. If mez is broken before MT has aggro from taunting, guess who gets smacked? <br>
<br>
4. Let the MT engage, break mez and cement aggro. After mez is broken, I usually let the MT smack away for a couple of seconds to help the aggro, lol. That way only one peep needs to be healed from melee dmg. If I steal aggro, I stop attacking, fd in my case, to let MT reestablish. <br>
<br>
5. Hit the assist several times during battles with multiple targets. There are times when the MT will change targets. As support, you have to be on your toes when it happens and trying to figure it out only by looking or clicking is not going to work very well. <br>
<br>
Other tips - <br>
<br>
1. Pay attention to mob positioning. Do not shove mobs over ledges or railings or through walls or doors. They aggro more mobs and you know the rest. Stop attacking and reposition. This works best if MT calls it, but called or not, don't be a party to the offense and let the MT know they need to call it. <br>
<br>
2. Watch for enrage. If you see a mob enrage or see it announced, be sure you are behind the mob or move behind the mob. If you can not get behind or to the side, you will need to assess the situation as to whether you keep attacking or stop and let others finish it. You can take alot of damage and die from an enraged mob very quickly since they riposte on every hit. <br>
<br>
<br>
Breaking mez at lower level encounters is not a big deal, especially with c3 on board and a zone close by. This makes it easy to instill poor melee habits with few consequences. But at higher level encounters, those poor habits will have disastrous effects on you and your party/raid. <br>
<br>
Everyone makes mistakes. Battles in tight quarters with lots of mobs breathin on ya can be confusing to us who are int challenged. Practice the above simple steps and you will make far fewer of them.  <br>
<br>
Be safe. <br>
<br>
