A few things I'd add:<br>
<!--EZCODE LIST START--><ul><li>You can assist by simply doing a &quot;/assist &lt;name&gt;&quot;. You do not have to target first. I've seen some folks say to use /target and then /assist - this works just fine, but you'll find it to be just slightly slower in getting the final target due to the separate commands. This usually isn't an issue, but I've seen it take a second or two in laggy situations.</li><li>Keep an assist key available that is NOT pretargeted to anyone in particular. You will find times in raids where your MA goes down and, for whatever reason, your SA is not the person to assist either. In such a case, you need to be ready to adjust quickly. This is a &quot;last resort&quot; kind of thing though.</li><li>Some things CAN be done to a mezzed mob without breaking mezz. As such, you'll find that your MA may turn and face a target, target it, but just stand there for a bit letting the mezzed mob sit for a moment. The MA may well be just stretching their fingers after mashing taunt so many times, but more likely they are waiting for the mob to be occluded, slowed, snared, tashed, malo'd or whatever - not to mention giving a large raid force time to catch up with them on targeting. This is why setting your assist to off (use &quot;/assist off&quot; )  is very important.</li><li>Most of the time a slight pause before joining the MA's attack is sufficient. If it's a dicey raid where you want to be more certain, have the MA set up a hot key that says something like &quot;You may now help a %t meet it's end&quot; or whatever - under this plan, folks should not attack until they see the message. Now, that said, keep your wits about you. Sometimes the MA will start and then receive a tell or just see something that distracts them and forget to send the message. Give them plenty of time to give the message, but if you find yourself 20 or 30 seconds in and no message, then, by all means, attack away unless you've been specifically told not too.</li><li>Unless your the MA, turn off any taunts you might have. I know a lot of melee combine their taunt in with another key (such as kick) - don't forget to remove that.</li><li>As Mnim indicated, don't be afraid to back up just a tad and to stop attacking if you grab unplanned aggro. Many non-warriors have aggro reducers available too (bards have a unresistable song for it, plus there are some aggro reducing weapons available. Rangers and SK's have spells, monks FD - I don't know whether Pally's have anything in that camp or not).</li></ul><!--EZCODE LIST END--><br>
<br>
